itational name from Chisholme near Hawick in southern Scotland, which derives its name from Old English <i>c̄se</i>, <i>cēse</i> ‘cheese’ (from Latin <i>caseus</i>) + <i>holm</i> ‘piece of dry land in a fen’ and refers to a waterside meadow good for dairy farming and hence for producing cheeses. In the 14th century members of this family migrated to the Highlands, settling in Strathglass, where their name was Gaelicized as <b>Siosal</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Chisom","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Chisholm  , once common in Yorkshire but now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chisam","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Chisholm  , once common in Cumbria but now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chisolm","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Chisholm  ."]},{"name":"Chisum","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Chisholm  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chislom","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Chisholm   or   Chisolm  ."]},{"name":"Chezem","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Chisholm  . Compare   Chisum  ."]},{"name":"Chism","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Chisholm  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Chisholm 5th of Chisholm was born in 1302, in Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland as the son of Alexander de Chisholm Lord of Chisholme in Roxburgh and Paxtoun in Berwickshire - 4th of Chisholme. He had at least 2 sons with Anne-nic-Robert Lauder of Ouarrelwood. He died in 1386, in Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1302–1386":"1302–1386","1310–1390":"1310–1390","1335–1393":"1335–1393","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1285":"1285","1340":"1340","1393":"1393","1390":"1390","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland","Chisholm, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Roxburghshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1302–1386":"1302–1386","1310–1390":"1310–1390","1335–1393":"1335–1393","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","about 1335":"noin 1335","1285":"1285","1340":"1340","1393":"1393","1390":"1390","about 1340":"noin 1340","Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland","Chisholm, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Roxburghshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1302–1386":"1302–1386","1310–1390":"1310–1390","1335–1393":"1335–1393","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","about 1335":"environ 1335","1285":"1285","1340":"1340","1393":"1393","1390":"1390","about 1340":"environ 1340","Paxton, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Paxton, Berwickshire, Écosse","Chisholm, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Roxburghshire, 